results.title: Daily bread
results.brief_description: Although Britain grows grain, most of the flour needed to make the bread which feeds the people of the British Isles is imported from overseas. This film follows the processes of manufacture from the time that the flour is unloaded in the ports until it leaves the baker’s van in the delivery-man’s basket.

results.title: Daguerre: the birth of photography = Daguerre: ou la naissan
results.brief_description: Traces the early history of photography, concentrating on the achievements of Joseph Niepce, who in 1822 invented the first permanent photograph. Louis Daguerre, who in 1838, developed a process for recording photographs on polished metal plates is shown with other innovators in the field.

results.brief_description: Shared custody, co-parenting, share-parenting…it goes by different names. results.title: Czechoslovakia: land and people
results.brief_description: Czechoslovakia is a country of two parts: Slovakia, a rugged mountainous land, and the Czech lands, a rich farming region with many industrial cities. With historical perspective we see the two regions as part of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, then as a democracy after World War I, and finally as a Communist state.

results.title: Cycles of the sky
results.creator_credit: David P. Stone and Coastal Community Colleges
results.brief_description:
Episode number 3 of Series “Universe: the infinite frontier: an introductory astronomy telecourse”.
This episode examines the influence that the Moon and its orbit has on the earth and the phenomena of lunar and solar eclipses. By observing the phases of the moon, early astronomers were able to divide the calendar into months, and the Earth’s rotation around the sun was responsible for the measurement of time into seasons. The Moon’s two types of orbit, Siberial and Sinotic are explained. Outlines how the Moon affects tides by the gravitational pull it exerts. Although readily explained scientifically, the solar and lunar eclipses still fascinate astronomers, professional and amateur alike, with their beauty and wonder.

results.title: Cybernetica
results.creator_credit: Peter M Sims, James Ritchie and British Transport Films
results.brief_description: Three young women converge on Paris, exploring as they travel, the wonders of a new age; the new railway age in which computers defeat by the speed of their decision making and contemporary evils of congestion, pollution and wasted space and time. “We can travel all we want, yet leave the land, the air and the sunshine undisturbed.”
